1
00:02:59,913 --> 00:03:01,847
<i>Attention, please.</i>

2
00:04:39,479 --> 00:04:41,208
- Mr. Hamilton?
- Yes?

3
00:06:56,652 --> 00:06:58,586
Scarsdale is next.

4
00:07:44,500 --> 00:07:46,434
Good day?

5
00:07:48,938 --> 00:07:50,872
- You?
- Very productive.

6
00:07:50,940 --> 00:07:53,966
Got the roses out in back
all trimmed.

7
00:07:55,177 --> 00:07:57,168
Oh, letter this morning from Sally.

8
00:07:57,246 --> 00:07:59,271
Sam's finished internship.

9
00:07:59,348 --> 00:08:01,748
Starts practice next week.

10
00:08:01,817 --> 00:08:05,082
Well, he should specialize.
That's the only thing now.

11
00:08:05,154 --> 00:08:08,783
Maybe he just wants to get
the feel of things.

12
00:08:08,858 --> 00:08:11,349
Our little girl's done all right.

13
00:08:18,534 --> 00:08:19,967
Something wrong?

14
00:08:23,939 --> 00:08:26,806
That phone call last night?

15
00:08:26,876 --> 00:08:28,309
What about it?

16
00:08:29,078 --> 00:08:33,344
I heard you pacing around in the study
afterwards till almost 2:00.

17
00:08:35,584 --> 00:08:40,078
Just a crazy prank.
Look, Emily, it was nothing.

18
00:09:13,589 --> 00:09:15,955
<i>Art? It's me again.</i>

19
00:09:17,493 --> 00:09:19,427
<i>Arthur?</i>

20
00:09:21,697 --> 00:09:23,995
Look, I don't know
who you are, but...

21
00:09:24,066 --> 00:09:26,261
- <i>Charlie Evans!</i>
- Stop saying that.

22
00:09:26,335 --> 00:09:29,099
Charlie Evans is dead.
Now I want you to stop this...

23
00:09:29,171 --> 00:09:31,833
or I'll be forced
to call the police.

24
00:09:31,907 --> 00:09:35,308
<i>There are two trophies</i>
<i>on the fireplace...</i>

25
00:09:35,378 --> 00:09:38,040
<i>near the tennis team picture.</i>

26
00:09:38,114 --> 00:09:40,207
<i>Pick up the phone</i>
<i>and walk over to them.</i>

27
00:09:43,386 --> 00:09:45,320
<i>Go ahead.</i>
<i>You know the cord will reach.</i>

28
00:09:49,392 --> 00:09:52,884
- <i>Are you there?</i>
- Yes.

29
00:09:52,962 --> 00:09:55,430
<i>In the picture,</i>
<i>you and I are standing...</i>

30
00:09:55,498 --> 00:09:58,296
<i>with our arms</i>
<i>around each other's shoulder.</i>

31
00:09:58,367 --> 00:10:01,803
<i>We're both wearing</i>
<i>the same kind of wristwatch.</i>

32
00:10:01,871 --> 00:10:05,307
<i>Remember, we gave them to each other</i>
<i>after winning the doubles at Princeton?</i>

33
00:10:05,374 --> 00:10:06,500
Yes.

34
00:10:06,575 --> 00:10:10,341
<i>Okay. Take</i>
<i>the doubles trophy there...</i>

35
00:10:10,413 --> 00:10:12,347
<i>and turn it over.</i>

36
00:10:15,017 --> 00:10:19,386
<i>One edge of the felt is loose.</i>
<i>Pull it back.</i>

37
00:10:25,127 --> 00:10:29,427
<i>You scratched it there, down in</i>
<i>the locker room after we won the finals.</i>

38
00:10:29,498 --> 00:10:31,090
<i>Remember?</i>

39
00:10:31,167 --> 00:10:33,101
<i>With your belt buckle.</i>

40
00:10:34,837 --> 00:10:37,670
L...

41
00:10:37,740 --> 00:10:39,674
I had forgotten.

42
00:10:39,742 --> 00:10:42,438
<i>I didn't.</i>

43
00:10:42,511 --> 00:10:44,445
It can't be you.

44
00:10:44,513 --> 00:10:47,607
<i>Okay, now. Listen very carefully.</i>

45
00:10:47,683 --> 00:10:50,015
- <i>Did you get the address today?</i>
- Yes.

46
00:10:50,085 --> 00:10:51,677
<i>Good.</i>

47
00:10:51,754 --> 00:10:54,348
<i>You're to use the name Wilson.</i>

48
00:10:54,423 --> 00:10:58,052
You can't be Charlie.
You just don't come back.

49
00:10:58,127 --> 00:10:59,560
<i>I'm alive!</i>

50
00:10:59,628 --> 00:11:03,257
<i>More alive than I've been</i>
<i>in the past 25 years.</i>

51
00:11:03,332 --> 00:11:05,698
<i>You've got to come tomorrow.</i>

52
00:11:06,936 --> 00:11:10,838
<i>Listen. If you don't show up,</i>
<i>that's it.</i>

53
00:11:12,241 --> 00:11:14,471
<i>Think, for Pete's sake.</i>

54
00:11:14,543 --> 00:11:17,637
<i>What have you got now? What?</i>

55
00:11:20,516 --> 00:11:22,347
I don't know.

56
00:11:22,418 --> 00:11:25,114
<i>Tomorrow. Just past noon.</i>

57
00:11:25,187 --> 00:11:28,281
<i>Remember, use the name Wilson.</i>

58
00:11:28,357 --> 00:11:31,918
L... don't know.

59
00:11:31,994 --> 00:11:33,928
<i>I won't call again, buddy.</i>

60
00:11:40,302 --> 00:11:41,667
Is it that call again?

61
00:11:46,675 --> 00:11:49,041
Stop cross-examining me
every time the phone rings.

62
00:11:49,111 --> 00:11:51,909
Understand?

63
00:11:51,981 --> 00:11:53,539
Perfectly.

64
00:11:57,586 --> 00:11:59,781
I'm sorry.

65
00:12:19,108 --> 00:12:21,042
Excuse me.

66
00:12:24,346 --> 00:12:26,280
You're excused.

67
00:12:31,320 --> 00:12:32,947
Any fever?

68
00:12:33,022 --> 00:12:36,219
No. Just old faithful.

69
00:12:36,292 --> 00:12:39,989
Make an appointment to see
Dr. Hogan tomorrow.

70
00:12:40,062 --> 00:12:42,826
I will.

71
00:12:42,898 --> 00:12:44,490
Promise?

72
00:12:46,502 --> 00:12:48,732
Promise. Thank you.

73
00:14:02,511 --> 00:14:04,411
Therefore...

74
00:14:05,480 --> 00:14:07,880
in view of the differential...

75
00:14:07,950 --> 00:14:09,884
between your present equity...

76
00:14:20,696 --> 00:14:23,062
Between your present equity
and the amount necessary...

77
00:14:23,131 --> 00:14:25,759
for capitalization...

78
00:14:27,302 --> 00:14:30,635
we cannot extend the loan
you require.

79
00:14:30,706 --> 00:14:32,640
Should your equity...

80
00:14:43,318 --> 00:14:44,683
Where?

81
00:14:44,753 --> 00:14:46,914
"Should your equity."

82
00:14:46,989 --> 00:14:49,719
Should your equity increase,
do not hesitate to call on us...

83
00:14:49,791 --> 00:14:52,783
for a personal reappraisal,
et cetera, et cetera.

84
00:14:52,861 --> 00:14:54,795
Standard closing.

85
00:14:57,833 --> 00:14:59,425
Yes, sir.

86
00:15:47,849 --> 00:15:50,181
My name is Wilson.

87
00:15:53,956 --> 00:15:55,890
I was told to...

88
00:16:00,162 --> 00:16:01,754
I was told to come here.

89
00:16:05,500 --> 00:16:07,627
Look, is this the place,
or isn't it?

90
00:16:14,142 --> 00:16:15,700
They aren't here anymore.

91
00:16:17,980 --> 00:16:19,914
I got it wrote down.

92
00:16:26,688 --> 00:16:28,622
Thank you.

93
00:16:31,827 --> 00:16:34,819
Move it! Let's go!

94
00:16:34,896 --> 00:16:39,560
Let's go, you bunch of idiots.
Get that beef cut down.

95
00:16:39,634 --> 00:16:44,196
Damn! Get that truck going and
get the meat the hell out of here!

96
00:16:44,272 --> 00:16:46,672
What are you gonna do,
take all day?

97
00:16:46,742 --> 00:16:49,575
Don't let those hooks fall off!
Let's move it.

98
00:16:50,479 --> 00:16:54,040
Okay, Johnny, get us
another truck up here.

99
00:16:54,116 --> 00:16:55,777
Tighten up with it.

100
00:16:55,851 --> 00:16:57,785
Ah, Mr. Wilson.

101
00:16:57,853 --> 00:16:59,718
Let's go on the truck with it.

102
00:16:59,788 --> 00:17:01,255
Surely this isn't...

103
00:17:01,323 --> 00:17:02,790
No, sir. Come with me.

104
00:17:02,858 --> 00:17:05,759
Let's go, Frank!
Move that truck off!

105
00:17:05,827 --> 00:17:08,261
Come on!
Let's hook it off! Hook off!

106
00:17:08,330 --> 00:17:11,629
Don't just stand there.
Move that beef off the line! Let's go!

107
00:17:11,700 --> 00:17:13,998
What are you, a bunch of jerks?

108
00:17:14,069 --> 00:17:16,003
Come on! Go! Go!

109
00:17:16,071 --> 00:17:18,562
Come on. Cut it down.
Coming in! Coming in!

110
00:17:18,640 --> 00:17:21,108
All right, come on. Move!
Keep moving that beef up.

111
00:17:21,176 --> 00:17:23,007
Cut it down. Let's go.

112
00:17:59,881 --> 00:18:02,679
Would you step in, please, sir?

113
00:18:02,751 --> 00:18:05,151
I'd much prefer to ride in front,
if you don't mind.

114
00:18:05,220 --> 00:18:09,088
I'm sorry, sir. The customers
are asked to ride in the back.

115
00:18:14,596 --> 00:18:17,292
Your hat, sir.
It's only a short ride.

116
00:18:17,365 --> 00:18:19,299
Thank you.

117
00:18:36,451 --> 00:18:39,147
We're here, sir.

118
00:18:45,627 --> 00:18:48,255
Would you take the elevator
to your left, sir?

119
00:19:10,385 --> 00:19:12,683
Ah, Mr. Wilson.
Will you come this way?

120
00:19:12,754 --> 00:19:14,346
Yes.

121
00:19:17,659 --> 00:19:21,220
There will be a short delay. Perhaps
you'd like some tea and a sandwich.

122
00:19:21,296 --> 00:19:23,230
- Thank you.
- Quite all right.

123
00:19:26,434 --> 00:19:28,368
Make yourself comfortable.

124
00:19:34,209 --> 00:19:36,143
Here we go.

125
00:22:47,345 --> 00:22:48,972
Pardon me.

126
00:22:49,047 --> 00:22:51,811
Could you tell me
the way out of this building?

127
00:22:57,889 --> 00:22:59,823
Excuse me.

128
00:22:59,891 --> 00:23:01,950
I was wondering if you could...

129
00:23:02,026 --> 00:23:04,893
Excuse me.
I'm trying to find...

130
00:23:08,866 --> 00:23:11,460
Excuse me. I'm trying to find
my way out of the building.

131
00:23:11,536 --> 00:23:14,164
I have a gentleman here
who wishes to leave the building.

132
00:23:14,239 --> 00:23:18,073
<i>That would be Mr. Wilson. Would you</i>
<i>have him return to Mr. Ruby's office?</i>

133
00:23:18,142 --> 00:23:20,474
<i>Mr. Ruby is waiting for him there.</i>

134
00:23:20,545 --> 00:23:23,412
They want you at the end
of the corridor again.

135
00:23:23,481 --> 00:23:25,415
Yes. All right.

136
00:23:34,826 --> 00:23:36,418
Thank you.

137
00:23:47,839 --> 00:23:50,637
Ah, there you are, Mr. Wilson.

138
00:23:50,708 --> 00:23:52,642
Come in. Please.

139
00:23:55,146 --> 00:23:57,080
Would you close the door?

140
00:24:03,921 --> 00:24:05,513
Please, sit down.

141
00:24:14,365 --> 00:24:15,957
My name is Ruby.

142
00:24:16,034 --> 00:24:19,902
I've been assigned to go over the
circumstances of your death with you.

143
00:24:19,971 --> 00:24:22,701
- What?
- I know this seems strange to you.

144
00:24:22,774 --> 00:24:26,141
That's why I'm here.
You probably have a lot of questions.

145
00:24:26,210 --> 00:24:30,408
Of course, the subject might appear
indelicate, but most of our clients...

146
00:24:30,481 --> 00:24:33,314
Get this straight.
I am not a client.

147
00:24:33,384 --> 00:24:36,876
Oh, precisely, Mr. Wilson.
You are not a client yet.

148
00:24:39,791 --> 00:24:44,091
Let me start by explaining
the cost factor involved.

149
00:24:44,162 --> 00:24:46,096
To begin with...

150
00:24:46,164 --> 00:24:50,362
the procedure
is a rather complex one.

151
00:24:50,435 --> 00:24:53,836
Seems to be your supper.
The chicken looks delicious.

152
00:24:53,905 --> 00:24:55,429
No, thank you.

153
00:24:55,506 --> 00:25:00,102
As I was saying, the cost runs
in the neighborhood of $30,000.

154
00:25:00,178 --> 00:25:03,909
I know this seems rather high,
but in addition to...

155
00:25:03,981 --> 00:25:07,348
the rather extensive
cosmetic renovation...

156
00:25:07,418 --> 00:25:09,613
by way of plastic surgery for you...

157
00:25:09,687 --> 00:25:12,679
CPS has to provide a fresh corpse...

158
00:25:12,757 --> 00:25:14,918
that perfectly matches...

159
00:25:14,992 --> 00:25:18,223
your physical dimensions
and medical specifications.

160
00:25:18,296 --> 00:25:20,093
CPS?

161
00:25:20,164 --> 00:25:21,654
Cadaver Procurement Section.

162
00:25:23,701 --> 00:25:25,430
Sure you don't want this chicken?

163
00:25:25,503 --> 00:25:26,868
Absolutely sure.

164
00:25:26,938 --> 00:25:28,872
Oh, pity.

165
00:25:28,940 --> 00:25:30,999
The next step...

166
00:25:31,075 --> 00:25:35,011
is the carefully
planned obliteration...

167
00:25:35,079 --> 00:25:38,276
of identifiable portions
of the cadaver...

168
00:25:38,349 --> 00:25:40,408
before it is found.

169
00:25:40,485 --> 00:25:42,885
Features, dental structure.

170
00:25:42,954 --> 00:25:45,184
Fingerprints.
We can't leave anything to chance.

171
00:25:45,256 --> 00:25:47,383
No, I guess not.

172
00:25:48,393 --> 00:25:50,588
Would you mind if...

173
00:25:52,363 --> 00:25:53,295
Please.

174
00:25:53,364 --> 00:25:55,525
Thank you.

175
00:25:55,600 --> 00:26:00,902
Now, there is a problem that
the circumstances of your death...

176
00:26:00,972 --> 00:26:02,872
must be simple.

177
00:26:02,940 --> 00:26:07,343
A simple accident, strangely enough,
is costly, Mr. Wilson.

178
00:26:07,412 --> 00:26:13,248
The trick lies in obliterating
just so much and no more, so that...

179
00:26:13,317 --> 00:26:16,844
an identification still can
be made based on...

180
00:26:16,921 --> 00:26:19,355
as I say,
general dimensions...

181
00:26:19,424 --> 00:26:23,053
plus a credible
sequence of events.

182
00:26:23,127 --> 00:26:25,186
Witnesses, et cetera.

183
00:26:25,263 --> 00:26:27,663
The whole thing must be
very carefully staged.

184
00:26:27,732 --> 00:26:30,064
We guarantee a death of this kind.

185
00:26:30,134 --> 00:26:34,127
Excuse me. Delicious!
They have a wonderful way...

186
00:26:34,205 --> 00:26:38,733
of baking cheese on it
so that it gets very crispy.

187
00:26:38,810 --> 00:26:44,214
Now, there are any number of ways
you can be found. Excuse me.

188
00:26:44,282 --> 00:26:47,774
I mean, your body can be found.

189
00:26:47,852 --> 00:26:52,755
The victim of some kind
of machinery, an explosion.

190
00:26:54,225 --> 00:26:55,866
A hunting misadventure.

191
00:26:58,636 --> 00:27:02,003
Oh, but I think these
are somewhat too gross for you.

192
00:27:02,073 --> 00:27:06,737
I had thought perhaps
a hotel room fire.

193
00:27:06,811 --> 00:27:10,042
Would you like me to outline
the circumstances?

194
00:27:10,114 --> 00:27:11,081
No, thank you.

195
00:27:11,148 --> 00:27:15,141
Oh, good. I was hoping
you would agree.

196
00:27:15,219 --> 00:27:19,451
No! I mean, I can't be sure.

197
00:27:19,523 --> 00:27:21,354
Oh, of course.

198
00:27:21,425 --> 00:27:25,486
We can't expect you
to decide all at once.

199
00:27:25,563 --> 00:27:30,660
Think it over. There's so much else
to be done, Mr. Wilson...

200
00:27:30,735 --> 00:27:33,863
but if I may say so...

201
00:27:33,938 --> 00:27:37,396
death selection may be the most
important decision in your life.

202
00:27:39,944 --> 00:27:42,572
Here are the trust instruments.

203
00:27:42,646 --> 00:27:44,580
Mr. Joliffe, Mr. Brown.

204
00:27:44,648 --> 00:27:46,741
My colleagues.

205
00:27:46,817 --> 00:27:48,910
Now, this is your revised will...

206
00:27:48,986 --> 00:27:52,183
drawn in accordance
with the requirements of the trust.

207
00:27:52,256 --> 00:27:55,384
They're all predated, of course,
to save you the trouble.

208
00:27:55,459 --> 00:27:57,450
It's standard procedure.

209
00:27:59,130 --> 00:28:01,394
Effective at the time
of your death...

210
00:28:01,465 --> 00:28:04,662
the trust provides
for very liberal settlements...

211
00:28:04,735 --> 00:28:06,669
on your wife and daughter...

212
00:28:06,737 --> 00:28:08,762
and more than sufficient funds...

213
00:28:08,839 --> 00:28:12,104
for your financial needs
in your new identity...

214
00:28:12,176 --> 00:28:16,772
from sums assigned to us
as your trustees.

215
00:28:16,847 --> 00:28:19,372
Insurance policies...

216
00:28:20,451 --> 00:28:21,884
annuities...

217
00:28:21,952 --> 00:28:23,886
real estate.

218
00:28:27,158 --> 00:28:29,092
If you'll sign right here.

219
00:28:51,482 --> 00:28:53,848
The staging here is rather
authentic, you'll see.

220
00:28:57,955 --> 00:29:00,685
Of course, the drug made it
easier to manipulate you...

221
00:29:00,758 --> 00:29:03,352
into the proper positions
and attitudes.

222
00:29:03,427 --> 00:29:05,827
Rest easy, Mr. Wilson.

223
00:29:10,034 --> 00:29:12,400
You did not ravage our girl.

224
00:29:17,641 --> 00:29:19,939
Of course, the photography
is not too professional...

225
00:29:20,010 --> 00:29:22,308
but I think it's clear enough.

226
00:29:35,726 --> 00:29:38,718
- So now it's...
- I have a message from Charlie.

227
00:29:43,100 --> 00:29:46,900
He wanted me to tell you
that rebirth is painful.

228
00:29:46,971 --> 00:29:49,235
You were going to say...

229
00:29:49,306 --> 00:29:52,742
"So now it's blackmail,"
eh, Mr. Wilson?

230
00:29:52,810 --> 00:29:57,008
- What would you call it?
- Just kind of insurance.

231
00:29:57,081 --> 00:30:01,450
Isn't it easier to go forward
when you know you can't go back?

232
00:30:01,518 --> 00:30:03,645
But you knew that, didn't you?

233
00:30:03,721 --> 00:30:08,181
The minute you hung up on Charlie
after that first call.

234
00:30:08,259 --> 00:30:10,193
Ah, sure you did.

235
00:30:17,501 --> 00:30:19,435
You're saying...

236
00:30:22,573 --> 00:30:24,700
I can never go back?

237
00:30:24,775 --> 00:30:27,403
Fact is, you really
don't want to go back.

238
00:30:29,480 --> 00:30:33,143
Sakes, boy, you owe yourself
this thing.

239
00:30:33,217 --> 00:30:36,209
Rebirth. Life again.

240
00:30:36,287 --> 00:30:39,313
Begin again,
all new, all different.

241
00:30:39,390 --> 00:30:41,324
The way you always wanted it.

242
00:30:41,392 --> 00:30:43,986
You've got another chance.

243
00:30:44,061 --> 00:30:46,757
Heck, nobody's gonna
miss you, are they?

244
00:30:46,830 --> 00:30:50,027
- My wife.
- What are you to her now?

245
00:30:56,340 --> 00:30:58,774
- We get along.
- What does that mean?

246
00:31:01,245 --> 00:31:03,179
There's my daughter.

247
00:31:09,987 --> 00:31:12,581
We don't see much of her, actually.

248
00:31:14,658 --> 00:31:18,219
She lives out west with her husband.

249
00:31:20,331 --> 00:31:22,356
She writes now and then...

250
00:31:24,201 --> 00:31:26,135
to let us...

251
00:31:27,771 --> 00:31:29,705
What are you to her now?

252
00:31:32,276 --> 00:31:35,404
Excuse an old fool prying, son...

253
00:31:35,479 --> 00:31:37,606
but what does it all mean?

254
00:31:41,418 --> 00:31:44,353
It can't mean anything now,
anymore.

255
00:31:44,421 --> 00:31:46,616
There's nothing anymore, is there?

256
00:31:46,690 --> 00:31:48,624
Anything at all?

257
00:31:51,695 --> 00:31:56,928
I expect to be president of the bank
before too long.

258
00:31:57,001 --> 00:32:00,459
And I have my boat in the summer.

259
00:32:02,006 --> 00:32:03,598
We have friends.

260
00:32:03,674 --> 00:32:05,608
Anything at all?

261
00:32:12,383 --> 00:32:14,317
Guess I...

262
00:32:15,486 --> 00:32:18,319
never thought much about it before.

263
00:32:21,125 --> 00:32:24,754
I leave Emily pretty much alone
to do what she...

264
00:32:30,968 --> 00:32:32,902
We get along, as I said.

265
00:32:34,204 --> 00:32:36,138
We hardly ever quarrel.

266
00:32:43,447 --> 00:32:46,541
Not that that's any...

267
00:32:46,617 --> 00:32:48,551
measure of our lives.

268
00:32:52,523 --> 00:32:54,457
Frankly...

269
00:32:56,427 --> 00:32:58,793
during the last few years, we...

270
00:33:01,031 --> 00:33:02,965
hardly ever...

271
00:33:09,106 --> 00:33:11,040
ever...

272
00:33:13,177 --> 00:33:17,079
l... I don't know
why I'm telling you this.

273
00:33:17,147 --> 00:33:19,513
Because you want to.
Go on.

274
00:33:24,922 --> 00:33:26,856
Ever...

275
00:33:33,030 --> 00:33:34,964
ever...

276
00:33:38,902 --> 00:33:40,836
show much affection.

277
00:33:46,777 --> 00:33:48,711
But as I said...

278
00:33:53,817 --> 00:33:55,409
Boat.

279
00:34:00,691 --> 00:34:02,283
And...

280
00:34:04,261 --> 00:34:08,721
So this is what happens
to the dreams of youth.

281
00:34:08,799 --> 00:34:10,767
Go on, son.
Let it out.

282
00:34:10,834 --> 00:34:13,394
Nothing to be ashamed of.

283
00:34:13,470 --> 00:34:15,404
Let it out.

284
00:34:20,177 --> 00:34:22,111
Time for a change.

285
00:34:24,648 --> 00:34:27,913
Now, look. They'll both
be well taken care of.

286
00:34:27,985 --> 00:34:30,351
They don't need you,
and you don't need them.

287
00:34:31,588 --> 00:34:34,250
You just can't help
each other anymore.

288
00:34:34,324 --> 00:34:38,317
Now, look, son.
You know what I'm saying is true.

289
00:34:38,395 --> 00:34:40,329
There's nothing anymore.

290
00:34:46,770 --> 00:34:49,830
What you need now is a good rest.

291
00:34:49,907 --> 00:34:52,137
A few things to be worked out
in the morning...

292
00:34:52,209 --> 00:34:55,838
but my boys will clear those up,
and you needn't worry none.

293
00:34:56,980 --> 00:34:58,572
Your boys?

294
00:35:01,652 --> 00:35:03,586
You're the head of it all?

295
00:35:03,654 --> 00:35:07,385
There never was a struggle in the soul
of a good man that wasn't hard.

296
00:35:07,457 --> 00:35:10,221
My papa told me that...

297
00:35:10,294 --> 00:35:12,319
and it's sure enough true.

298
00:35:12,396 --> 00:35:15,432
Believe me, son. I know.

299
00:35:18,535 --> 00:35:19,968
I believe you.

300
00:35:21,238 --> 00:35:23,172
That's fine.

301
00:37:30,233 --> 00:37:35,466
You know, Mr. Wilson, you represent
something of a milestone around here.

302
00:37:35,539 --> 00:37:37,530
When the bandages are removed...

303
00:37:37,607 --> 00:37:40,542
I think you'll be
more than pleased.

304
00:37:40,610 --> 00:37:44,910
In fact, I expect you to be prancing
around here like a stud bull.

305
00:37:46,516 --> 00:37:49,451
Now, it's gonna take a while,
so try to be patient...

306
00:37:49,519 --> 00:37:51,578
until we get you ready
for the world again.

307
00:37:52,389 --> 00:37:54,323
Now, don't do that!

308
00:37:54,391 --> 00:37:56,325
You can't talk because
we've extracted all your teeth...

309
00:37:56,393 --> 00:37:59,226
and given you a complete
vocal cord resection.

310
00:38:00,330 --> 00:38:02,594
Give the tissues time
to pull together.

311
00:38:03,900 --> 00:38:06,664
Now, you got a new set
of permanent teeth.

312
00:38:06,736 --> 00:38:09,864
In a week, you won't know
the difference. Thank you.

313
00:38:09,940 --> 00:38:13,034
That's what hurts
the most right now.

314
00:38:13,109 --> 00:38:15,043
Everything's different.

315
00:38:15,111 --> 00:38:18,672
When the first healing's over, we'll
start conditioning for muscle tone.

316
00:38:20,650 --> 00:38:22,584
Yes, yes. Those too.

317
00:38:22,652 --> 00:38:24,586
Fingerprints.

318
00:38:24,654 --> 00:38:26,588
Even your signature.

319
00:38:27,657 --> 00:38:30,956
Little thing we did with
the tensor ligaments of the hand.

320
00:38:42,806 --> 00:38:47,266
The orbicularis oris started to sag,
so we tightened them with ligatures.

321
00:38:47,344 --> 00:38:49,073
Yeah.

322
00:38:49,145 --> 00:38:51,670
Then we worked on the mandible
to square up the bone.

323
00:39:01,891 --> 00:39:04,325
Well, I never.

324
00:39:04,394 --> 00:39:07,659
Holy mackerel, I don't know
how you boys do it.

325
00:39:07,731 --> 00:39:10,199
Doc, it's a masterpiece.

326
00:39:10,266 --> 00:39:12,200
Good work.

327
00:39:33,690 --> 00:39:37,421
Easy does it.
You'll be all right, son.

328
00:39:53,543 --> 00:39:56,944
Your scars and hematomas will
disappear in a couple of weeks.

329
00:39:58,181 --> 00:40:01,742
After several months
of physical conditioning...

330
00:40:01,818 --> 00:40:03,752
the process will be complete.

331
00:40:28,344 --> 00:40:32,280
My name is Davalo.
I'm your guidance advisor.

332
00:40:32,348 --> 00:40:36,580
This is about your future career.

333
00:40:36,653 --> 00:40:38,951
I'm afraid I haven't thought
very much about that.

334
00:40:39,022 --> 00:40:41,889
Oh, yes, you have, sir.
Permit me.

335
00:40:42,959 --> 00:40:46,622
<i>I want a ball, a big red one.</i>

336
00:40:46,696 --> 00:40:48,891
Whoops.

337
00:40:48,965 --> 00:40:51,957
I'm afraid we picked this up
a little too early.

338
00:40:52,035 --> 00:40:53,969
Sit down. We recorded
these regressions...

339
00:40:54,037 --> 00:40:58,030
under pentothal
and caffeine sodium benzoate.

340
00:40:58,108 --> 00:41:00,406
At first, there's always
a touch of the infantile...

341
00:41:00,477 --> 00:41:03,469
but later on, we progress
to a more mature...

342
00:41:03,546 --> 00:41:06,071
expressional infrastructure.

343
00:41:07,517 --> 00:41:09,451
Ah, here we are.

344
00:41:10,820 --> 00:41:15,052
<i>What would you like</i>
<i>to do most of all?</i>

345
00:41:15,992 --> 00:41:18,017
<i>Of anything in the whole world?</i>

346
00:41:21,464 --> 00:41:25,560
<i>I'd like to be</i>
<i>a tennis pro, I guess.</i>

347
00:41:25,635 --> 00:41:30,095
<i>Yes. That's what</i>
<i>I'd like best of all.</i>

348
00:41:31,541 --> 00:41:35,068
<i>And suppose you couldn't be?</i>

349
00:41:35,145 --> 00:41:38,581
<i>What else would you choose?</i>

350
00:41:40,683 --> 00:41:46,315
- <i>I guess I'd like to paint stuff.</i>
- <i>Pictures?</i>

351
00:41:46,389 --> 00:41:50,348
<i>Pictures and things.</i>

352
00:41:50,426 --> 00:41:55,772
Well, I think the creative wish
pattern is pretty self-evident.

353
00:41:58,608 --> 00:42:02,738
You mean, l...
I ought to be a painter?

354
00:42:02,812 --> 00:42:04,109
Exactly!

355
00:42:10,053 --> 00:42:14,217
You see, painting allows you
a basic creative outlet...

356
00:42:14,290 --> 00:42:18,886
as well as an environment in which
these sublimations will have free vent.

357
00:42:19,662 --> 00:42:24,326
Now, let's take a look at the program
we've worked out for you.

358
00:42:24,400 --> 00:42:26,334
Certificates of study.

359
00:42:30,406 --> 00:42:31,896
Abroad.

360
00:42:32,975 --> 00:42:36,467
Notices of first six one-man shows.

361
00:42:37,780 --> 00:42:42,376
Your pictures are realistic
in treatment...

362
00:42:42,452 --> 00:42:45,944
but deal with poetic imagery
in choice of subject.

363
00:42:46,022 --> 00:42:50,356
Not that I pretend to be
a critic of painting.

364
00:42:55,865 --> 00:42:57,298
These diplomas...

365
00:42:59,802 --> 00:43:02,965
from reputable universities...

366
00:43:03,039 --> 00:43:05,803
They can't be forged.

367
00:43:05,875 --> 00:43:11,279
I assure you, every item
is bona fide and valid.

368
00:43:12,415 --> 00:43:15,350
How could I even approach
such a professional level?

369
00:43:15,418 --> 00:43:20,117
Simple. You are already established
in a position of some dignity.

370
00:43:20,189 --> 00:43:25,126
Nothing conspicuous. Just a solid,
mildly successful sort of thing.

371
00:43:25,194 --> 00:43:28,721
You will be supplied
with fresh paintings periodically.

372
00:43:28,798 --> 00:43:32,199
In time, you'll
perfect your own style.

373
00:43:32,268 --> 00:43:34,566
Surreal, primitive,
impressionistic, whatever.

374
00:43:34,637 --> 00:43:38,437
It will be a transition
from this present work.

375
00:43:38,508 --> 00:43:43,104
You see, you don't have to
prove anything anymore.

376
00:43:44,180 --> 00:43:47,843
You are accepted.

377
00:43:47,917 --> 00:43:52,479
You will be
in your own new dimension.

378
00:43:54,223 --> 00:43:56,191
You're a bachelor.

379
00:43:56,259 --> 00:43:58,784
Birth certificate.
The only son...

380
00:43:58,861 --> 00:44:00,886
of deceased parents, and so forth.

381
00:44:00,963 --> 00:44:03,523
In short...

382
00:44:03,599 --> 00:44:06,727
you are alone in the world...

383
00:44:06,802 --> 00:44:10,829
absolved of all responsibility...

384
00:44:10,907 --> 00:44:14,104
except to your own interest.

385
00:44:18,014 --> 00:44:19,675
Isn't that marvelous?

386
00:44:20,316 --> 00:44:23,752
<i>Your studio is</i>
<i>in Malibu, California.</i>

387
00:44:23,819 --> 00:44:28,017
<i>Quite luxurious, very private.</i>

388
00:44:28,090 --> 00:44:30,786
<i>You'll make your own adjustment</i>
<i>in your own way...</i>

389
00:44:30,860 --> 00:44:33,090
<i>in your own time.</i>

390
00:44:33,162 --> 00:44:36,325
<i>Oh, you'll be</i>
<i>self-conscious at first.</i>

391
00:44:36,399 --> 00:44:38,697
<i>Don't worry.</i>

392
00:44:38,768 --> 00:44:42,033
<i>It will wear off.</i>
<i>And remember, you've got...</i>

393
00:44:42,104 --> 00:44:47,474
<i>what almost every middle-aged man</i>
<i>in America would like to have:</i>

394
00:44:47,543 --> 00:44:49,408
<i>Freedom.</i>

395
00:44:49,478 --> 00:44:51,412
<i>Real freedom.</i>

396
00:44:54,350 --> 00:44:57,012
<i>Ah, it's been a pleasure.</i>

397
00:44:57,086 --> 00:44:59,020
Pillow, Mr. Wilson?

398
00:45:00,856 --> 00:45:02,790
Yes, thank you.

399
00:45:54,944 --> 00:45:56,969
Tony!

400
00:46:03,119 --> 00:46:04,882
Hey there, you old rascal!

401
00:46:04,954 --> 00:46:07,479
Slow down. Where's the fire?

402
00:46:07,556 --> 00:46:11,390
Can't wait to get back to them
pretty little models, huh?

403
00:46:11,460 --> 00:46:13,394
Uh-oh, I am late.

404
00:46:13,462 --> 00:46:17,796
If I didn't have to catch a plane,
I'd make you buy me a drink, by God!

405
00:46:17,867 --> 00:46:19,732
See you soon. Got to run.

406
00:46:24,206 --> 00:46:25,798
<i>Welcome home, Mr. Wilson.</i>

407
00:46:25,875 --> 00:46:28,469
My name is John.
I've been assigned to help you.

408
00:46:52,735 --> 00:46:54,259
It's very nice.

409
00:46:54,337 --> 00:46:56,897
I think you'll be
quite comfortable, sir.

410
00:47:06,449 --> 00:47:08,383
Do you like your studio?

411
00:47:10,052 --> 00:47:12,486
- Yes.
- Perhaps you'd like to freshen up...

412
00:47:12,555 --> 00:47:14,489
and have a drink.

413
00:47:23,899 --> 00:47:28,165
Afterward, I'll try to clear up any
point on which you may have curiosity.

414
00:47:36,011 --> 00:47:38,502
The bath is through here.

415
00:47:38,581 --> 00:47:40,640
I'll unpack these for you later.

416
00:47:40,716 --> 00:47:42,308
Fine.

417
00:47:55,331 --> 00:47:57,299
How long will you be here?

418
00:47:57,366 --> 00:48:00,460
John, sir.
For as long as you need me.

419
00:48:00,536 --> 00:48:03,232
The company is fully aware
that you may have problems at first...

420
00:48:03,305 --> 00:48:05,330
and will spare no effort
to help you solve them.

421
00:48:05,408 --> 00:48:06,807
Thank you.

422
00:48:06,876 --> 00:48:08,343
Yes, sir.

423
00:48:30,332 --> 00:48:31,924
Yes, sir?

424
00:48:33,135 --> 00:48:38,072
I had a curious experience
at the airport.

425
00:48:38,140 --> 00:48:39,937
What was that?

426
00:48:41,243 --> 00:48:45,145
Well, I was accosted by a man
who called me by name.

427
00:48:46,849 --> 00:48:49,784
He seemed to know me,
and I'm certain I've never met him.

428
00:48:53,022 --> 00:48:55,718
I suppose it was a mistake
on his part.

429
00:48:55,791 --> 00:48:57,725
So it would appear, sir.

430
00:49:37,666 --> 00:49:40,692
What kind of people live here?

431
00:49:40,769 --> 00:49:44,569
Professionals.
Some in business. Some write.

432
00:49:44,640 --> 00:49:47,939
No artists, I hope.

433
00:49:48,010 --> 00:49:50,410
I think you are the only one, sir.

434
00:50:19,708 --> 00:50:22,302
If I may suggest, sir...

435
00:50:22,377 --> 00:50:27,076
perhaps you'd like to give a cocktail
party for the immediate neighbors.

436
00:50:27,149 --> 00:50:29,743
Oh, well, l...

437
00:50:29,818 --> 00:50:32,844
I'd better get myself
used to things first.

438
00:50:34,056 --> 00:50:36,183
Later on, maybe.

439
00:50:36,258 --> 00:50:38,192
As you wish, sir.

440
00:51:48,297 --> 00:51:50,197
That's very good, sir.

441
00:51:50,265 --> 00:51:51,857
Thank you.

442
00:51:57,306 --> 00:52:01,675
Wouldn't you enjoy meeting
some of the people here, sir?

443
00:52:01,743 --> 00:52:04,644
I told you I'm not ready yet, John.

444
00:52:04,713 --> 00:52:07,614
I'll do this in my own way
and in my own time.

445
00:52:08,784 --> 00:52:10,376
Of course, sir.

446
00:53:25,794 --> 00:53:27,386
Hello.

447
00:53:37,472 --> 00:53:38,905
Hey, wait.

448
00:53:41,009 --> 00:53:42,943
I'm sorry about back there.

449
00:53:46,682 --> 00:53:49,116
How about if we try it again?

450
00:53:50,886 --> 00:53:52,820
Hello.

451
00:53:52,888 --> 00:53:54,321
I'm Nora Marcus.

452
00:53:57,726 --> 00:53:59,489
I'm...

453
00:53:59,561 --> 00:54:01,188
Tony Wilson.

454
00:54:05,667 --> 00:54:07,601
- Walk?
- Sure.

455
00:54:20,682 --> 00:54:24,846
Ocean, I love you!
You're beautiful!

456
00:54:24,920 --> 00:54:27,150
Beautiful!

457
00:54:29,057 --> 00:54:32,925
All that power,
and she's got all the answers.

458
00:54:35,297 --> 00:54:37,094
Got a question!

459
00:54:53,148 --> 00:54:55,582
What did you ask?

460
00:54:55,650 --> 00:54:57,584
Oh, a tough one.

461
00:54:59,054 --> 00:55:01,215
"Who and what is Tony Wilson?"

462
00:55:03,859 --> 00:55:05,793
And what did it say?

463
00:55:09,364 --> 00:55:12,299
It told me to mind my own business.

464
00:55:28,517 --> 00:55:32,578
<i>That was my life.</i>
<i>Two boys, ages ten and twelve.</i>

465
00:55:32,654 --> 00:55:36,112
<i>Successful and indulgent husband.</i>

466
00:55:36,191 --> 00:55:40,059
<i>A beautiful house,</i>
<i>complete with microwave oven...</i>

467
00:55:40,128 --> 00:55:44,155
intercom, station wagon, et cetera.

468
00:55:44,232 --> 00:55:46,166
Ad infinitum.

469
00:55:55,350 --> 00:55:56,578
And?

470
00:55:56,651 --> 00:55:59,711
I made myself a cup of coffee,
dressed and left.

471
00:56:01,189 --> 00:56:02,622
That was four years ago.

472
00:56:02,691 --> 00:56:04,659
You never went back.

473
00:56:04,726 --> 00:56:07,320
I've seen them from
time to time, but...

474
00:56:07,395 --> 00:56:10,091
it's different now.

475
00:56:10,165 --> 00:56:12,099
Maybe because I'm different.

476
00:56:14,736 --> 00:56:17,102
I don't expect you to understand.

477
00:56:17,172 --> 00:56:19,106
I think I do.

478
00:56:20,408 --> 00:56:21,807
You?

479
00:56:21,876 --> 00:56:24,606
An artist?

480
00:56:24,679 --> 00:56:26,510
Why should you understand?

481
00:56:26,581 --> 00:56:30,017
You spent your whole life being.

482
00:56:31,186 --> 00:56:34,280
You don't know anything
about me, really.

483
00:56:34,356 --> 00:56:36,187
Yes, I do.

484
00:56:37,692 --> 00:56:39,626
It's all right there in your face.

485
00:56:40,795 --> 00:56:43,263
What is?

486
00:56:43,331 --> 00:56:45,265
Now you're fishing.

487
00:56:45,333 --> 00:56:46,925
No. Seriously.

488
00:56:49,003 --> 00:56:50,436
This may hurt a little.

489
00:56:52,307 --> 00:56:54,241
I agreed to take my chances.

490
00:56:57,846 --> 00:56:59,780
Madam Marcus will read the leaves.

491
00:57:16,965 --> 00:57:19,593
What kind of a man is he?

492
00:57:23,104 --> 00:57:26,301
There's grace
in the line and color...

493
00:57:26,374 --> 00:57:29,639
but it doesn't emerge pure.

494
00:57:31,045 --> 00:57:34,811
It pushes at the edge of something
still tentative.

495
00:57:36,251 --> 00:57:39,084
Unresolved. As if...

496
00:57:40,321 --> 00:57:44,655
somewhere in the man,
there is still a key...

497
00:57:44,726 --> 00:57:46,216
unturned.

498
00:57:49,297 --> 00:57:50,889
That's quite an analysis.

499
00:57:53,568 --> 00:57:55,297
Not really.

500
00:57:55,370 --> 00:57:59,807
When you come to think of it,
it sort of fits everybody, doesn't it?

501
00:58:09,250 --> 00:58:10,877
It's very nice here.

502
00:58:17,692 --> 00:58:21,025
The good things always happen
with the rain.

503
00:58:44,786 --> 00:58:47,414
When will I see you again?

504
00:58:47,489 --> 00:58:51,084
I'm going to Santa Barbara tomorrow.
There's a kind of gathering.

505
00:58:51,159 --> 00:58:52,592
Can I come?

506
00:58:53,761 --> 00:58:55,456
It's going to be very wild.

507
00:58:55,530 --> 00:58:59,330
Maybe that's part of
turning the key.

508
00:59:44,946 --> 00:59:48,746
